- We have

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 &= (2n)^3 - 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) - 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 - 12n^2 + 6n - 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  and

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n+1)^3 &= (2n)^3 + 3(2n)^2 + 3(2n) + 1 \hspace{2em} \\[6pt]
  &= 8n^3 + 12n^2 + 6n + 1\end{aligned}
  $$

  Summing our expressions for $(2n-1)^3$ and $(2n+1)^3$, we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 8n^3 - \cancel{12n^2} + 6n - \cancel{1} + 8n^3 + \cancel{12n^2} + 6n + \cancel{1}
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \answer{(2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 = 16n^3 + 12n} \hspace{2em}\end{aligned}
  $$

- Let $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ be two consecutive odd integers for some
$n \in \mathbb{Z}$.
  The sum of the cubes of $2n-1$ and $2n+1$ is

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{6.4em} (2n-1)^3 + (2n+1)^3 &= 16n^3 + 12n \hspace{2em} [\text{by part (a)}] \\[6pt]
  &= 4n(4n^2 + 3) \hspace{2.22em} [\text{multiple of $4$}]\end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence the sum of the cubes of any two consecutive odd integers is
divisible by four.

- To write $f$ in the desired form we must complete the square

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
      f(x)&=4x-x^2-1\\[6pt]
      &=-(x^2-4x)-1\\[6pt]
      &=-[(x-2)^2-(2)^2]-1\\[6pt]
      &=-(x-2)^2+4-1\\[6pt]
      &=\answer{3-(x-2)^2}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- 
  - We can find the $y-$coordinate by evaluating the function at both $x=0$ and $x=2$.

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &&f(0)&=3-(0-2)^2&\hspace{-1em} &&f(2)&= 3-(2-2)^2&  \\[6pt]
        &&&=-1&\hspace{-1em} && &= 3& 
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Hence the coordinates are $\answer{A(0,-1)\text{ and }B(2,3)}$

    $$
    \begin{align*}
    \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - We can make a quick sketch of $f$
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/41d8354f-4cec-4922-8437-0ca160d21c7a/images/8a3d4b08-1625-4d2d-b1a0-4194dc8e9e19/AA1290-a.JPEG)


    We have the $y-$intercept already.
    And the gradient of the line through $A$ and $B$ is

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        m&=\dfrac{3-(-1)}{2-0}\\[6pt]
        m&=2 
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Therefore, the line through $A$ and $B$ is $\answer{y=2x-1}$

    $$
    \begin{align*}
    \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

  - The shaded area, seen below, shows the area we need to find
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/41d8354f-4cec-4922-8437-0ca160d21c7a/images/7d705ca2-0e34-498c-9547-5edd23168ba9/AA1290-a2.JPEG)


    To find the area we evaluate the following definite integral, where $A_x$ and $B_x$ are the $x-$coordinates of points $A$ and $B$ respectively

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &=\int_{A_x}^{B_x} (\mathrm{f}(x)-\mathrm{g}(x)) \,dx \\[4pt]
        &=\int_{0}^{2} (4x-x^2-1-(2x-1)) \,dx\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}\\[4pt]
        &=\int_{0}^{2} (2x-x^2) \,dx
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Using the inverse power rule and substituting in the limits we get

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        &=\left[x^2-\dfrac{1}{3}x^3\right]_{0}^{2}\\[4pt]
         &=(2)^2-\dfrac{1}{3}(2)^3-\left((0)^2-\dfrac{1}{3}(0)^3\right) \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[4pt]
         &=\answer{\dfrac{4}{3}\text{ units}^2}\hspace{1em}\text{...as required}
    \end{align*}
    $$


- We can make a quick sketch of the new region enclosed by $f(x)$ and the new (horizontal) $g(x)$.
  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/41d8354f-4cec-4922-8437-0ca160d21c7a/images/93eaf720-1029-402e-8f97-65cddb8026ba/AA1290-a3.JPEG)


  We now evaluate the definite integral, where $C_x$ and $D_x$ are the $x-$coordinates of points $C$ and $D$ respectively

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\int_{C_x}^{D_x} (\mathrm{f}(x)-\mathrm{g}(x)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{1}^{3} (4x-x^2-1-(2)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{1}^{3} (4x-x^2-3) \,dx \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}\\[3pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Using the inverse power rule, to integrate each term and substitute in the limits, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\left[2x^2-\frac{1}{3}x^3-3x\right]_{1}^{3}\\[3pt]
          &=2(3)^2-\dfrac{1}{3}(3)^3-3(3)-\left((2(1)^2-\dfrac{1}{3}(1)^3-3(1)\right) \\[3pt]
          &=18-9-9-(2-\frac{1}{3}-3)\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[3pt]
          &=\answer{\dfrac{4}{3}\text{ units}^2}\hspace{1em}\text{...as required}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The diagram below shows a region bound by $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ and the points $E(a, f(a))$ and $F(a+2, f(a+2)))$.
  The function $f$ needs to be used to calculate the $y-$coordinate values of $E$ and $F$.
  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/41d8354f-4cec-4922-8437-0ca160d21c7a/images/7597d9d0-8ed4-4fea-8e36-94f1a14efc4c/AA1290-a4.JPEG)


  To find the area we need to find the linear function $g(x)$ in terms of $a$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  $\mathrm{g}(x)$ is of the form $g(x)=m_gx+c_g$.
  Where the gradient, $m_g$, is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      m_g&=\dfrac{y_2+y_1}{x_2-x_1}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{\mathrm{f}(a+2)-\mathrm{f}(a)}{a+2-a}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{(3-a^2)-(3-(a-2)^2))}{2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Simplifying we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\dfrac{-a^2+(a-2)^2}{2}\\[3pt]
      &=\dfrac{-a^2+a^2-4a+4}{2}\\[3pt]
      m_g&=2-2a \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[3pt]    
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  Using the point $A(a, f(a))$ we can find the $y-$intercept, $c_g$, of $g(x)$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      y&=(2-2a)x+c_g\\[3pt]
      \mathrm{f}(a)&=(2-2a)a+c_g\\[3pt]
      3-(a-2)^2&=(2-2a)a+c_g\\[3pt]    
      c_g&=3-(a-2)^2-2a+2a^2\\[3pt]    
      c_g&=a^2+2a-1 \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\\[3pt] 
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  The function $g(x)$ in terms of $a$ is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \mathrm{g}(x)=(2-2a)x+a^2+2a-1
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The shaded area is given by the following definite integral

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\int_{E_x}^{F_x} (f(x)-g(x)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (4x-x^2-1-((2-2a)x+a^2+2a-1)) \,dx \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Simplifying we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (4x-x^2-1-(2x-2ax+a^2+2a-1)) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (2x-x^2+2ax-a^2-2a) \,dx\\[3pt]
      &=\int_{a}^{a+2} (-x^2+(2a+2)x-a^2-2a) \,dx
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now we can integrate each term, using the inverse power rule, and substitute in the limits.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =\left[-\dfrac{1}{3}x^3+\dfrac{2a+2}{2}x^2-x(a^2+2a)\right]_{a}^{a+2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =-\dfrac{1}{3}(a+2)^3+(a+1)(a+2)^2-(a+2)(a^2+2a)-...\\
  ...\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3+(a+1)a^2-a(a^2+2a)\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Expanding and simplifying we gradient

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =-\dfrac{1}{3}(a^3+6a^2+12a+8)+a^3+5a^2+8a+4-(a^3+4a^2+4a)-...\\
  ...\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3+a^3+a^2-a^3-2a^2\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We continue to collect any like terms and simplify to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  =\cancel{-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3}-2a^2-4a-\dfrac{8}{3}+a^2+4a+4-...\\
  ...\left(\cancel{-\dfrac{1}{3}a^3}-a^2\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=\cancel{-2a^2}-\cancel{4a}-\dfrac{8}{3}+\cancel{a^2}+\cancel{4a}+4+\cancel{a^2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\
  &=-\dfrac{8}{3}+4\\
  &=\answer{\dfrac{4}{3} \,\text{units}^2}\hspace{3em}\text{...as required}
  \end{align*}
  $$
